T9 304 Anonymous25 : A dozen years ago I developed and demoed the first ragdoll physics system that worked.
T9 305 Anonymous25 : animats.com  Among other things, I'm responsible for the "ragdoll falling downstairs" cliche; that started with a demo I did in 1997.
T9 306 Anonymous25 : I looked at ragdolls as a first step.
T9 307 Anonymous25 : I was expecting game development to go in the direction of physically-based characters driven by active control of character muscles.
T9 308 Anonymous25 : That hasn't happened.
T9 309 Anonymous25 : The problem is partly technical and partly dramatic.
T9 310 Anonymous25 : The dramatic part I encountered in dealing with Hollywood types.
T9 311 Anonymous25 : What directors want is to specify the start and end conditions; the job of the system is to realistically get the character to the desired ending mark.
T9 312 Anonymous25 : In real-world stunt work, there are wires, guides, and rails that make things go the way the director wants, even when that's not physically realistic.
T9 313 Anonymous25 : When that's not enough, cuts are used to conceal the lack of realism.
T9 314 Anonymous25 : Physics systems are inherently unidirectional - you keep working forward from the current state.
T9 315 Anonymous25 : This is fundamentally incompatible with directorial control.
T9 316 Anonymous25 : As a result, the
T9 317 Anonymous25 : trend in character animation has been to get enough motion capture data to cover the things you want the character to do, and use a motion splicing engine to patch the pieces together.
T9 318 Anonymous25 : This, incidentally, was first used in Godzilla, the movie, for the baby 'zillas.
T9 319 Anonymous25 : That's become more or less the standard approach for games.
T9 320 Anonymous25 : Using a character control AI to drive the character's muscles realistically has been attempted, but with modest success.
T9 321 Anonymous25 : Motion Factory tried this in the 1990s; their system was only kinematic, and not too successful.
T9 322 Anonymous25 : Havok is trying it now.
T9 323 Anonymous25 : For this to work, you need computerized muscle control good enough to drive a real-world robot, like Big Dog.
T9 324 Anonymous25 : And then it has to look good from an aesthetic perspective.
T9 325 Anonymous25 : It's really a hard robotics problem, which is why I was interested in it in the first place.
T9 326 Anonymous25 : From a gameplay perspective, if you take the physics seriously, you lose the "superhero" capabilities of game characters.
T9 327 Anonymous25 : Jump off a balcony, and don't expect to land on your feet.
T9 328 Anonymous25 : Jumping up to a balcony?
T9 329 Anonymous25 : Forget it.
T9 330 Anonymous25 : Hand-to-hand combat works about as well as it does at the dojo.
T9 331 Anonymous25 : "Your left foot was too far forward for that throw.
